Japan plans to go to the meeting of the International Whaling Commission (IWC) in South Korea in June asking to double its kill of about 440 minke whales a year for so-called scientific purposes, and also add humpback and fin whales to the list.
Tokyo is believed to have the votes needed to get its request approved at the Ulsan meeting.
"Our position on research whaling will not change just because of foreign pressure," said Takanori Nagatomo, deputy director at the Far Seas Fisheries Division of the agency.
Australian Prime Minister John Howard took the unusual step of intervening personally.
